The question that has puzzled many a mind!
Unfortunately, a serious answer: the concept of "terminal velocity" applies to objects falling under gravity in a medium like air or water.

It's the maximum speed an object can reach as it falls, A terminal velocity occurs when the force of gravity pulling the object down is balanced by the frictional force of the surrounding fluid (in this case,air) pushing the object up.

Now,2001 film Monty Python and the Holy Grail, The idea of asking about the terminal velocity of an "unladen swallow" (meaning a swallow bird not carrying any load) was a comedic plot device to illustrate the absurdity of a question.
Now,2019 study published in The Journal of Experimental Biology estimated the terminal velocity of a House Sparrow (Passer domesticus), which is similar in size and shape to a swallow.

Now, an unladen swallow (a bird,not a cargo-carrying vessel) is a living creature that flies, A flying bird does not fall under gravity like an inanimate object would, so there is no terminal velocity for an unladen swallow in the classical sense.
